[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] We believe that only an **open-source solution to data movement** can cover the long tail of data sources while empowering data engineers to customize existing connectors.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] Our ultimate vision is to help you move data from any source to any destination — whether that destination is a data warehouse, a data lake, or an AI agent.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] Airbyte provides a catalog of 600+ connectors for APIs, databases, data warehouses, data lakes, and AI applications.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] (Airbyte Connections UI) *Screenshot taken from Airbyte Cloud*.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] Try it out yourself with our demo app, visit our full documentation, and learn more about recent announcements.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] See our registry for a full list of connectors already available in Airbyte or Airbyte Cloud.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] The Airbyte community can be found in the Airbyte Community Slack, where you can ask questions and voice ideas.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] You can also ask for help in our Airbyte Forum.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] Airbyte's roadmap is publicly viewable on GitHub.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] For videos and blogs on data engineering and building your data stack, check out Airbyte's Content Hub, YouTube, and sign up for our newsletter.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] If you've found a problem with Airbyte, please open a GitHub issue.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] To contribute to Airbyte and see our Code of Conduct, please see the contributing guide.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] We have a list of good first issues that contain bugs that have a relatively limited scope.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] This is a great place to get started, gain experience, and get familiar with our contribution process.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] When submitting a pull request, please ensure that Airbyte maintainers have write access to your branch.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] This allows us to apply formatting fixes and dependency updates directly, significantly speeding up the review and approval process.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] To enable write access on your PR from Airbyte maintainers, please check the "Allow edits from maintainers" box when submitting from your PR.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] You must also create your PR from a fork in your **personal GitHub account** rather than an organization account, or else you will not see this option.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] The requirement to create from your personal fork is based on GitHub's additional security restrictions for PRs created from organization forks.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] For more information about the GitHub security model, please see the GitHub documentation page regarding PRs from forks.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] For more details on contribution requirements, please see our contribution workflow documentation.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] Airbyte takes security issues very seriously.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] **Please do not file GitHub issues or post on our public forum for security vulnerabilities**.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] Email `security@airbyte.io` if you believe you have uncovered a vulnerability.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] In the message, try to provide a description of the issue and ideally a way of reproducing it.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] The security team will get back to you as soon as possible.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] Airbyte Enterprise also offers additional security features (among others) on top of Airbyte open-source.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] See the LICENSE file for licensing information, and our FAQ for any questions you may have on that topic.
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] Airbyte would not be possible without the support and assistance of other open-source tools and companies!
[src:airbyte-integration/blob-readme-md] Visit our thank you page to learn more about how we build Airbyte.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The decision to integrate data tends to arise when the volume, complexity (that is, big data) and need to share existing data explodes.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] It has become the focus of extensive theoretical work, and numerous open problems remain unsolved.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Data integration encourages collaboration between internal as well as external users.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The data being integrated must be received from a heterogeneous database system and transformed to a single coherent data store that provides synchronous data across a network of files for clients.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] A common use of data integration is in data mining when analyzing and extracting information from existing databases that can be useful for Business information.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Issues with combining heterogeneous data sources, often referred to as information silos, under a single query interface have existed for some time.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] In the early 1980s, computer scientists began designing systems for interoperability of heterogeneous databases.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The first data integration system driven by structured metadata was designed in 1991 at the University of Minnesota for the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] IPUMS used a data warehousing approach, which extracts, transforms, and loads data from heterogeneous sources into a unique view schema so data from different sources become compatible.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] By making thousands of population databases interoperable, IPUMS demonstrated the feasibility of large-scale data integration.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The data warehouse approach offers a tightly coupled architecture because the data are already physically reconciled in a single queryable repository, so it usually takes little time to resolve queries.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The data warehouse approach is less feasible for data sets that are frequently updated, requiring the extract, transform, load (ETL) process to be continuously re-executed for synchronization.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Difficulties also arise in constructing data warehouses when one has only a query interface to summary data sources and no access to the full data.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] This problem frequently emerges when integrating several commercial query services like travel or classified advertisement web applications.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] A trend began in 2009 favoring the loose coupling of data and providing a unified query-interface to access real time data over a mediated schema (see Figure 2), which allows information to be retrieved directly from original databases.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] This is consistent with the SOA approach popular in that era.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] This approach relies on mappings between the mediated schema and the schema of original sources, and translating a query into decomposed queries to match the schema of the original databases.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Such mappings can be specified in two ways: as a mapping from entities in the mediated schema to entities in the original sources (the "Global-as-View" (GAV) approach), or as a mapping from entities in the original sources to the mediated schema (the "Local-as-View" (LAV) approach).
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The latter approach requires more sophisticated inferences to resolve a query on the mediated schema, but makes it easier to add new data sources to a (stable) mediated schema.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] As of 2010, some of the work in data integration research concerns the semantic integration problem.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] This problem addresses not the structuring of the architecture of the integration, but how to resolve semantic conflicts between heterogeneous data sources.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] For example, if two companies merge their databases, certain concepts and definitions in their respective schemas like "earnings" inevitably have different meanings.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] In one database it may mean profits in dollars (a floating-point number), while in the other it might represent the number of sales (an integer).
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] A common strategy for the resolution of such problems involves the use of ontologies which explicitly define schema terms and thus help to resolve semantic conflicts.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] This approach represents ontology-based data integration.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] On the other hand, the problem of combining research results from different bioinformatics repositories requires bench-marking of the similarities, computed from different data sources, on a single criterion such as positive predictive value.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] This enables the data sources to be directly comparable and can be integrated even when the natures of experiments are distinct.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] As of 2011, it was determined that current data modeling methods were imparting data isolation into every data architecture in the form of islands of disparate data and information silos.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] This data isolation is an unintended artifact of the data modeling methodology that results in the development of disparate data models.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Disparate data models, when instantiated as databases, form disparate databases.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Enhanced data model methodologies have been developed to eliminate the data isolation artifact and to promote the development of integrated data models.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] One enhanced data modeling method recasts data models by augmenting them with structural metadata in the form of standardized data entities.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] As a result of recasting multiple data models, the set of recast data models will now share one or more commonality relationships that relate the structural metadata now common to these data models.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Commonality relationships are a peer-to-peer type of entity relationships that relate the standardized data entities of multiple data models.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Multiple data models that contain the same standard data entity may participate in the same commonality relationship.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] When integrated data models are instantiated as databases and are properly populated from a common set of master data, then these databases are integrated.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Since 2011, data hub approaches have been of greater interest than fully structured (typically relational) Enterprise Data Warehouses.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Since 2013, data lake approaches have risen to the level of Data Hubs.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] (See all three search terms popularity on Google Trends.) These approaches combine unstructured or varied data into one location, but do not necessarily require an (often complex) master relational schema to structure and define all data in the Hub.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Data integration plays a big role in business regarding data collection used for studying the market.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Converting the raw data retrieved from consumers into coherent data is something businesses try to do when considering what steps they should take next.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Organizations are more frequently using data mining for collecting information and patterns from their databases, and this process helps them develop new business strategies to increase business performance and perform economic analyses more efficiently.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Compiling the large amount of data they collect to be stored in their system is a form of data integration adapted for Business intelligence to improve their chances of success.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Consider a web application where a user can query a variety of information about cities (such as crime statistics, weather, hotels, demographics, etc.).
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Traditionally, the information must be stored in a single database with a single schema.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] But any single enterprise would find information of this breadth somewhat difficult and expensive to collect.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Even if the resources exist to gather the data, it would likely duplicate data in existing crime databases, weather websites, and census data.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] A data-integration solution may address this problem by considering these external resources as materialized views over a virtual mediated schema, resulting in "virtual data integration".
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] This means application-developers construct a virtual schema—the *mediated schema*—to best model the kinds of answers their users want.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Next, they design "wrappers" or adapters for each data source, such as the crime database and weather website.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] These adapters simply transform the local query results (those returned by the respective websites or databases) into an easily processed form for the data integration solution (see figure 2).
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] When an application-user queries the mediated schema, the data-integration solution transforms this query into appropriate queries over the respective data sources.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Finally, the virtual database combines the results of these queries into the answer to the user's query.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] This solution offers the convenience of adding new sources by simply constructing an adapter or an application software blade for them.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] It contrasts with ETL systems or with a single database solution, which require manual integration of entire new data set into the system.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The virtual ETL solutions leverage virtual mediated schema to implement data harmonization; whereby the data are copied from the designated "master" source to the defined targets, field by field.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Advanced data virtualization is also built on the concept of object-oriented modeling in order to construct virtual mediated schema or virtual metadata repository, using hub and spoke architecture.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Each data source is disparate and as such is not designed to support reliable joins between data sources.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Therefore, data virtualization as well as data federation depends upon accidental data commonality to support combining data and information from disparate data sets.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Because of the lack of data value commonality across data sources, the return set may be inaccurate, incomplete, and impossible to validate.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] One solution is to recast disparate databases to integrate these databases without the need for ETL.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The recast databases support commonality constraints where referential integrity may be enforced between databases.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The recast databases provide designed data access paths with data value commonality across databases.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The theory of data integration forms a subset of database theory and formalizes the underlying concepts of the problem in first-order logic.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Applying the theories gives indications as to the feasibility and difficulty of data integration.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] While its definitions may appear abstract, they have sufficient generality to accommodate all manner of integration systems, including those that include nested relational / XML databases and those that treat databases as programs.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Connections to particular databases systems such as Oracle or DB2 are provided by implementation-level technologies such as JDBC and are not studied at the theoretical level.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Data integration systems are formally defined as a tuple $\left\langle G,S,M\right\rangle$ where G is the global (or mediated) schema, S is the heterogeneous set of source schemas, and M is the mapping that maps queries between the source and the global schemas.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Both G and S are expressed in languages over alphabets composed of symbols for each of their respective relations.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The mapping M consists of assertions between queries over G and queries over S .
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] When users pose queries over the data integration system, they pose queries over G and the mapping then asserts connections between the elements in the global schema and the source schemas.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] A database over a schema is defined as a set of sets, one for each relation (in a relational database).
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The database corresponding to the source schema S would comprise the set of sets of tuples for each of the heterogeneous data sources and is called the *source database*.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Note that this single source database may actually represent a collection of disconnected databases.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The database corresponding to the virtual mediated schema G is called the *global database*.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The global database must satisfy the mapping M with respect to the source database.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The legality of this mapping depends on the nature of the correspondence between G and S .
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Two popular ways to model this correspondence exist: *Global as View* or GAV and *Local as View* or LAV.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] GAV systems model the global database as a set of views over S .
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] In this case M associates to each element of G a query over S .
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Query processing becomes a straightforward operation due to the well-defined associations between G and S .
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The burden of complexity falls on implementing mediator code instructing the data integration system exactly how to retrieve elements from the source databases.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] If any new sources join the system, considerable effort may be necessary to update the mediator, thus the GAV approach appears preferable when the sources seem unlikely to change.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] In a GAV approach to the example data integration system above, the system designer would first develop mediators for each of the city information sources and then design the global schema around these mediators.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] For example, consider if one of the sources served a weather website.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The designer would likely then add a corresponding element for weather to the global schema.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Then the bulk of effort concentrates on writing the proper mediator code that will transform predicates on weather into a query over the weather website.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] This effort can become complex if some other source also relates to weather, because the designer may need to write code to properly combine the results from the two sources.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] On the other hand, in LAV, the source database is modeled as a set of views over G .
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] In this case M associates to each element of S a query over G .
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Here the exact associations between G and S are no longer well-defined.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] As is illustrated in the next section, the burden of determining how to retrieve elements from the sources is placed on the query processor.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The benefit of an LAV modeling is that new sources can be added with far less work than in a GAV system, thus the LAV approach should be favored in cases where the mediated schema is less stable or likely to change.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] In an LAV approach to the example data integration system above, the system designer designs the global schema first and then simply inputs the schemas of the respective city information sources.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Consider again if one of the sources serves a weather website.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The designer would add corresponding elements for weather to the global schema only if none existed already.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Then programmers write an adapter or wrapper for the website and add a schema description of the website's results to the source schemas.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The complexity of adding the new source moves from the designer to the query processor.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The theory of query processing in data integration systems is commonly expressed using conjunctive queries and Datalog, a purely declarative logic programming language.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] One can loosely think of a conjunctive query as a logical function applied to the relations of a database such as " $f(A,B)$ where $A<B$ ".
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] If a tuple or set of tuples is substituted into the rule and satisfies it (makes it true), then we consider that tuple as part of the set of answers in the query.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] While formal languages like Datalog express these queries concisely and without ambiguity, common SQL queries count as conjunctive queries as well.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] In terms of data integration, "query containment" represents an important property of conjunctive queries.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] A query A contains another query B (denoted $A\supset B$ ) if the results of applying B are a subset of the results of applying A for any database.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The two queries are said to be equivalent if the resulting sets are equal for any database.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] This is important because in both GAV and LAV systems, a user poses conjunctive queries over a *virtual* schema represented by a set of views, or "materialized" conjunctive queries.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Integration seeks to rewrite the queries represented by the views to make their results equivalent or maximally contained by our user's query.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] This corresponds to the problem of answering queries using views (AQUV).
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] In GAV systems, a system designer writes mediator code to define the query-rewriting.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Each element in the user's query corresponds to a substitution rule just as each element in the global schema corresponds to a query over the source.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Query processing simply expands the subgoals of the user's query according to the rule specified in the mediator and thus the resulting query is likely to be equivalent.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] While the designer does the majority of the work beforehand, some GAV systems such as Tsimmis involve simplifying the mediator description process.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] In LAV systems, queries undergo a more radical process of rewriting because no mediator exists to align the user's query with a simple expansion strategy.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The integration system must execute a search over the space of possible queries in order to find the best rewrite.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The resulting rewrite may not be an equivalent query but maximally contained, and the resulting tuples may be incomplete.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] As of 2011 the GQR algorithm is the leading query rewriting algorithm for LAV data integration systems.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] In general, the complexity of query rewriting is NP-complete.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] If the space of rewrites is relatively small, this does not pose a problem — even for integration systems with hundreds of sources.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] Large-scale questions in science, such as real world evidence, global warming, invasive species spread, and resource depletion, are increasingly requiring the collection of disparate data sets for meta-analysis.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] This type of data integration is especially challenging for ecological and environmental data because metadata standards are not agreed upon and there are many different data types produced in these fields.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] National Science Foundation initiatives such as Datanet are intended to make data integration easier for scientists by providing cyberinfrastructure and setting standards.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The Research Data Alliance, has more recently explored creating global data integration frameworks.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-integration] The OpenPHACTS project, funded through the European Union Innovative Medicines Initiative, built a drug discovery platform by linking datasets from providers such as European Bioinformatics Institute, Royal Society of Chemistry, UniProt, WikiPathways and DrugBank.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] In computing, a **pipeline**, also known as a **data pipeline**, is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] The elements of a pipeline are often executed in parallel or in time-sliced fashion.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Some amount of buffer storage is often inserted between elements.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Pipelining is a commonly used concept in everyday life.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] For example, in the assembly line of a car factory, each specific task—such as installing the engine, installing the hood, and installing the wheels—is often done by a separate work station.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] The stations carry out their tasks in parallel, each on a different car.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Once a car has had one task performed, it moves to the next station.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Variations in the time needed to complete the tasks can be accommodated by "buffering" (holding one or more cars in a space between the stations) and/or by "stalling" (temporarily halting the upstream stations), until the next station becomes available.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Suppose that assembling one car requires three tasks that take 20, 10, and 15 minutes, respectively.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Then, if all three tasks were performed by a single station, the factory would output one car every 45 minutes.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] By using a pipeline of three stations, the factory would output the first car in 45 minutes, and then a new one every 20 minutes.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] As this example shows, pipelining does not decrease the latency, that is, the total time for one item to go through the whole system.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] It does however increase the system's throughput, that is, the rate at which new items are processed after the first one.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] In computing, a pipeline or data pipeline is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] If a pipeline consists of idempotent steps, these can be rerun without altering the outcome beyond the initial run.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] This is advantageous in terms of reliability and maintenance.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Since the throughput of a pipeline cannot be better than that of its slowest element, the designer should try to divide the work and resources among the stages so that they all take the same time to complete their tasks.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] In the car assembly example above, if the three tasks took 15 minutes each, instead of 20, 10, and 15 minutes, the latency would still be 45 minutes, but a new car would then be finished every 15 minutes, instead of 20.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Under ideal circumstances, if all processing elements are synchronized and take the same amount of time to process, then each item can be received by each element just as it is released by the previous one, in a single clock cycle.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] That way, the items will flow through the pipeline at a constant speed, like waves in a water channel.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] In such "wave pipelines", no synchronization or buffering is needed between the stages, besides the storage needed for the data items.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] More generally, buffering between the pipeline stages is necessary when the processing times are irregular, or when items may be created or destroyed along the pipeline.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] For example, in a graphics pipeline that processes triangles to be rendered on the screen, an element that checks the visibility of each triangle may discard the triangle if it is invisible, or may output two or more triangular pieces of the element if they are partly hidden.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Buffering is also needed to accommodate irregularities in the rates at which the application feeds items to the first stage and consumes the output of the last one.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] The buffer between two stages may be simply a hardware register with suitable synchronization and signalling logic between the two stages.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] When a stage A stores a data item in the register, it sends a "data available" signal to the next stage B.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Once B has used that data, it responds with a "data received" signal to A.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Stage A halts, waiting for this signal, before storing the next data item into the register.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Stage B halts, waiting for the "data available" signal, if it is ready to process the next item but stage A has not provided it yet.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] If the processing times of an element are variable, the whole pipeline may often have to stop, waiting for that element and all the previous ones to consume the items in their input buffers.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] The frequency of such pipeline stalls can be reduced by providing space for more than one item in the input buffer of that stage.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Such a multiple-item buffer is usually implemented as a first-in, first-out queue.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] The upstream stage may still have to be halted when the queue gets full, but the frequency of those events will decrease as more buffer slots are provided.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Queueing theory can tell the number of buffer slots needed, depending on the variability of the processing times and on the desired performance.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] If some stage takes (or may take) much longer than the others, and cannot be sped up, the designer can provide two or more processing elements to carry out that task in parallel, with a single input buffer and a single output buffer.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] As each element finishes processing its current data item, it delivers it to the common output buffer, and takes the next data item from the common input buffer.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] This concept of "non-linear" or "dynamic" pipeline is exemplified by shops or banks that have two or more cashiers serving clients from a single waiting queue.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] In some applications, the processing of an item Y by a stage A may depend on the results or effect of processing a previous item X by some later stage B of the pipeline.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] In that case, stage A cannot correctly process item Y until item X has cleared stage B.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] This situation occurs very often in instruction pipelines.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] For example, suppose that Y is an arithmetic instruction that reads the contents of a register that was supposed to have been modified by an earlier instruction X.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Let A be the stage that fetches the instruction operands, and B be the stage that writes the result to the specified register.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] If stage A tries to process instruction Y before instruction X reaches stage B, the register may still contain the old value, and the effect of Y would be incorrect.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] In order to handle such conflicts correctly, the pipeline must be provided with extra circuitry or logic that detects them and takes the appropriate action.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Rather than halt while waiting for X to be finished, stage A may guess whether the branch will be taken or not, and fetch the next instruction Y based on that guess.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] If the guess later turns out to be incorrect (hopefully rarely), the system would have to backtrack and resume with the correct choice.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] To be effectively implemented, data pipelines need a CPU scheduling strategy to dispatch work to the available CPU cores, and the usage of data structures on which the pipeline stages will operate on.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] For example, UNIX derivatives may pipeline commands connecting various processes' standard IO, using the pipes implemented by the operating system.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Some operating systems may provide UNIX-like syntax to string several program runs in a pipeline, but implement the latter as simple serial execution, rather than true pipelining—namely, by waiting for each program to finish before starting the next one.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Lower level approaches may rely on the threads provided by the operating system to schedule work on the stages: both thread pool-based implementations or on a one-thread-per-stage are viable, and exist.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Other strategies relying on cooperative multitasking exist, that do not need multiple threads of execution and hence additional CPU cores, such as using a round-robin scheduler with a coroutine-based framework.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] In this context, each stage may be instantiated with its own coroutine, yielding control back to the scheduler after finishing its round task.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] This approach may need careful control over the process' stages to avoid them abuse their time slice.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] A pipelined system typically requires more resources (circuit elements, processing units, computer memory, etc.) than one that executes one batch at a time, because its stages cannot share those resources, and because buffering and additional synchronization logic may be needed between the elements.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Moreover, the transfer of items between separate processing elements may increase the latency, especially for long pipelines.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] The additional complexity cost of pipelining may be considerable if there are dependencies between the processing of different items, especially if a guess-and-backtrack strategy is used to handle them.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Indeed, the cost of implementing that strategy for complex instruction sets has motivated some radical proposals to simplify computer architecture, such as RISC and VLIW.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] Compilers also have been burdened with the task of rearranging the machine instructions so as to improve the performance of instruction pipelines.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] In recent years the demands on applications and their underlying hardware have been significant.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] For example, building pipelines with single node applications that trawl through the data row by row is no longer feasible with the volume and variety of big data.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] However, with the advent of data analytics engines such as Hadoop, or more recently Apache Spark, it's been possible to distribute large datasets across multiple processing nodes, allowing applications to reach heights of efficiency several hundred times greater than was thought possible before.
[src:airbyte-integration/data-pipeline] The effect of this today is that even a mid-level PC using distributed processing in this fashion can handle the building and running of big data pipelines.
[src:airbyte-integration/docs-airbyte-com] Airbyte is an open source data replication platform and context layer for AI agents.
[src:airbyte-integration/docs-airbyte-com] Equip your agents to query, search, and act on your data in real-time, or replicate data from hundreds of sources into warehouses, lakes, and databases.
